<paragraph id="CFF2D4F3676FC4F6BD777DB1D89B6B58" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="E9A489C5AFCEB26DE60F1EE8EB7F5109" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="B6F97661BD1125349D80E38206C5D476" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Abdomen</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Oval, slightly longer than broad, with dense appressed pile.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A176E6A069112E9897F7E4F7DA8B373" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="DAD044B2296F7D1B4C9798C5748FD90E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="86EDE140F69B2D8033C508287A0D02E3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Male genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Surstyli symmetric; aedeagus segmented, with phallapodeme separated from basiphallus and distiphallus; phallapodeme rounded, not banana-shaped; well-developed ctenidion present in male genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="933C5103ABCF75BE2A0D2B9469307F50" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="3254BD037955052D052A2482C2249390" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">FEMALE.</emphasis>
As male except for the following character states. Eyes widely separated; frons fully brown pruinose; face without pruinosity; metafemur only slightly swollen, never curved or with apicoventral ridge; metatibia never modified; always without tubercle on hind trochanter; wing always less microtrichose with species-specific characters as in species description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B45D58301EAD0A3FC0AD905E9246300E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="69605C30D8532078C741C7433931586C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6DD01EB11155FF21FBEB6909D4630C18" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Generally, species of 
<taxonomicName id="7671C65478C0199650018F21A3288CC6" authority="Bigot, 1882" authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1882" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Romaleosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Romaleosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0F6322354B6C7820CF652F28DF788B72" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Romaleosyrphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show little variation in pile color patterns, at least given the limited material we worked with. However, there are a few exceptions. 
<taxonomicName id="35A2F36F04AC20ED221841ED24203E17" authority="Bigot, 1882" authorityName="Moran &amp; Thompson" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Romaleosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Romaleosyrphus soletluna" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soletluna">
<emphasis id="F5CC3AC090B4FBB755E5CE23C9DAA4BF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Romaleosyrphus soletluna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Moran &amp; Thompson, sp. nov. is drastically dimorphic in pile coloration with a mostly orange morph and mostly black morph. The single northern specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="87762CC1477DD796225C4799D5F9293A" authority="Bigot, 1882" authorityName="Moran &amp; Skevington" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Giglio-Tos" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Romaleosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Romaleosyrphus arctophiloides" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arctophiloides">
<emphasis id="9A257CE6C3F1040EADC9D49E518EF1A2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Romaleosyrphus arctophiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Sierra Madre Occidental has fully black pilose legs. This contrasts with the population surrounding Mexico City, from which the type was collected, which have a streak of yellow pile at the base of the fore and mid femora. Finally, pile color on the proepimeron is variable inside multiple species with observed character states being fully yellow, fully black or a mix of the two. We suspect that additional material will likely show proepimeron pile color to be variable in all species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
